3<lb/>
these mountains and vallies!<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">The Unknown</hi>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Philo<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>
            </del> The reason is obvious enough<lb/>
Man is formed by his institutions, and<lb/>
moral and political causes almost create<lb/>
his character, Whereas <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">nature</hi> is governed<lb/>
by fixed laws. The Atmosphere, the<lb/>
the mountains, the vallies, the plains, the<lb/>
degrees of heat and cold, with small differences<lb/>
have continued the same, <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">385 S</add> | &amp; whether peopled<lb/>
or deserted, this soil will always produce<lb/>
fruits or flowers, wild or cultivated<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Poet.</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Phil.</add> If the exterior of the globe is<lb/>
liable to only small changes, there must<lb/>
be a permanency in the elements of<lb/>
things; something give must be ideas unalterable<lb/>
Will you give us some ideas <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Philochemicus</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
respecting this part of your philosophy, -<lb/>
which are the true elements of things?<lb/>
if there be a permanency or constancy<lb/>
in the arrangements of nature, matter<lb/>
cannot be infinite either in its divisibility<lb/>
or changes: pray give us some light on<lb/>
these obscure and difficult matters.<lb/>
The Unknown<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <hi rend="underline">Philo</hi>
            </del> I shall willingly enter upon this<lb/>
subject. I cannot demonstrate to you<lb/>
what are the true elements of things; but<lb/>
I can exhibit to you those substances, which<lb/>
as we cannot decompose them, are elementary<lb/>
for us: mathematically considered, it appears<lb/>
possible to prove the infinite divisibility of<lb/>
matter; but our mechanical means of division<lb/>
are extremely limited. There is every reason<lb/>
to believe that our powers of chemical<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
4<lb/>
Ed.<lb/>
decomposition are far from having reached<lb/>
their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ultimatum</hi>; yet in the operations<lb/>
of nature, as well as in those of art,<lb/>
Certain substances appear to be unchangeable<lb/>
Thus, if we take a metal such as iron, and<lb/>
dissolve it in a acid, or sublime it in<lb/>
union with an <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#chemical_078"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag13">
          elastic fluid
          
        </term>
            </rs>, or make<lb/>
it enter into a hundred combinations,<lb/>
it may still be recovered unaltered in<lb/>
its properties, the same in substance<lb/>
and in quantity. The test of a body being<lb/>
indecomposable is, that in all chemical<lb/>
changes it increases in weight, or its<lb/>
changes result from its combining with<lb/>
new matter. Thus when <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#chemical_012"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag14">
          Mercury
          
        </term>
            </rs> is<lb/>
converted into a red powder by being<lb/>
heated in the air, it gains in weight.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
The test of a body being compound is,<lb/>
that in assuming new forms it loses<lb/>
weight; thus when the olive coloured substance<lb/>
called <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#chemical_440"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag15">
          oxide of silver
          
        </term>
            </rs> is converted into<lb/>
silver by heat, it weighs less than before<lb/>
but in all cases either of gain or loss of<lb/>
weight, the circumstance depends either<lb/>
upon matter absorbed, or matter emitted<lb/>
which is either solid, fluid, or <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#misc_109"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag16">
          aeriform
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
and which can be always collected and weighted<lb/>
the metals, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#chemical_037"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag17">
          Sulphur
          
        </term>
            </rs>, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#chemical_151"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag18">
          Phosphorous
          
        </term>
            </rs>, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag19"
                ref="#chemical_054"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag19">
          Carbon
          
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
Silenium, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#chemical_424"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag20">
          iodine
          
        </term>
            </rs>, Brome, &amp; certain<lb/>
elastic fluids are the only substances<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which</del> as far as our knowledge extends<lb/>
