Phil.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Poet.</del> What is your idea of the cause<lb/>
of this difference of weight. Do you<lb/>
suppose their particles likewise of different<lb/>
sizes, or that they are of the same size<lb/>
and have a different quantity of pores, or size<lb/>
that their figures are different?<lb/>
The Unknown<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Philo<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>
            </hi> ]The question cannot be answered<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
6<lb/>
except by conjectures. At some time<lb/>
possibly we may be able to solve them<lb/>
by an hypothesis which will satisfactorily<lb/>
explain the chemical phenomena; but<lb/>
as we can never see the elementary<lb/>
particles of bodies, our reasoning upon<lb/>
them must be founded upon analogies<lb/>
derived from mechanics, &amp; the idea<lb/>
that small indivisible particles follow<lb/>
the same laws of motion as the masses<lb/>
which they compose.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag55"
                ref="#misc_063"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag55">
          Eubathes
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Pol.</del> I think it is contrary to the<lb/>
principles of sound philosophy to reason<lb/>
in this way. In mathematics it is<lb/>
always supposed that lines are composed<lb/>
from points, surfaces from lines, solids<lb/>
from surfaces; yet the elements bear<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
no relation to their compounds. Again<lb/>
in light: according to your principle,<lb/>
white light would be composed of many<lb/>
particles, of white light; whereas analysis<lb/>
proves it to be composed of various<lb/>
coloured particles, each differing from<lb/>
the other. On the hypothesis of<lb/>
Boscovitch, which is well explained in<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Institutio Physica</hi> of Mako<lb/>
Matter, as well as I recollect, is supposed<lb/>
to be composed of indivisible points endowed<lb/>
with attraction and repulsion, which are<lb/>
assumed to be both physical &amp; chemical<lb/>
elements.<lb/>
The Unknown<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Philo.</del> You mistake me if you suppose<lb/>
I have adopted a system like the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Homooia</hi> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag56"
                ref="#person_605"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag56" type="person">
          Anaxagoras
        </name>
            </rs>, &amp; that I suppose<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
7<lb/>
the elements to be physical molecules<lb/>
endowed with the properties of the bodies<lb/>
we believe to be indecomposable. On the<lb/>
contrary, I neither suppose in their<lb/>
figure nor colour, - both would imply<lb/>
a power of reflecting light: I consider<lb/>
them with Bocovitch - merely as points<lb/>
possessing weight &amp; attractive &amp; repulsive<lb/>
powers, &amp; composing according to the<lb/>
circumstances of their arrangements either<lb/>
spherules or regular solids, &amp; capable<lb/>
of assuming either one form or the<lb/>
other, all that is necessary for the<lb/>
doctrines of the corpuscular philosophy<lb/>
is of suppose the molecules which we<lb/>
are not able to decompose, Spherical<lb/>
molecules, &amp; that by the arrangement<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
of spherical molecules regular solids<lb/>
are formed; &amp; that the molecules have<lb/>
certain attractive &amp; repulsive powers which<lb/>
correspond to negative &amp; positive electricity<lb/>
this is not mere supposition unsupported<lb/>
by experiments; these are various facts<lb/>
which give probability to the idea, which<lb/>
I shall now state to you. The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">first</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">fact</hi> is, that all bodies are capable<lb/>
of being rendered fluid by a certain<lb/>
degree of heat, which supposes a freedom<lb/>
of motion in their particles that cannot<lb/>
be well explained except by supposing<lb/>
them spherical in the fluid state.<lb/>
The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">second</hi> fact is, that all bodies in<lb/>
becoming solid are capable of assuming<lb/>
regular <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">polyedral</add> forms, <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which could not happen</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
8<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">left then molecules arranged themselves</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">polyedral form</del>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">The third fact</hi> is<lb/>
that all c<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">h</del>rystal<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">l</add>ine bodies present<lb/>
regular electrical poles. And the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
