               <name xml:id="tag66" type="person">
          Lucretius
        </name>
            </rs> attributes to accident the<lb/>
discovery of the fusion of the metals. A<lb/>
person in touching a shell fish observes<lb/>
that it emits a purple liquid, &amp; applies<lb/>
this purple liquid as a dye. Hence<lb/>
the Tyrian purple. Clay is observed to<lb/>
harden in the fire; &amp; hence the invention<lb/>
of bricks, which could hardly fail<lb/>
ultimately to lead to the discovery of<lb/>
porcelain. Even glass, the most perfect<lb/>
&amp; most beautiful of those manufactures<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="30"
                xml:id="pb-30"
                facs="#i30"/>
            <lb/>
you call chemical is said to have been<lb/>
discovered by accident. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag67"
                ref="#person_277"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag67" type="person">
          Theophrastus
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
states that some merchants who were<lb/>
