                facs="#i33"/>
            <lb/>
29<lb/>
of this discovery, there can be little<lb/>
doubt that it was developed by a<lb/>
scientific worker in metals. Vitruvius<lb/>
tells us that the cerulean, a colour made<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag71"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag71">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs>, which exists in perfection in<lb/>
all the oil paintings of the Greeks &amp; Romans<lb/>
for the mummies of the Egyptians, was<lb/>
discovered by an Egyptian King. There<lb/>
is therefore every reason to believe that<lb/>
it was not the result of accidental<lb/>
combination, but of experiments made<lb/>
for improving or producing colours<lb/>
Amongst the ancient philosophers many<lb/>
discoveries are attributed to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag72"
                ref="#person_182"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag72" type="person">
          Democritus
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
