                xml:id="pb-44"
                facs="#i44"/>
            <lb/>
was scarcely known before it was applied<lb/>
by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag81"
                ref="#person_005"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag81" type="person">
          Berthollet
        </name>
            </rs> to bleaching. Scarcely was<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag82"
                ref="#chemical_016"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag82">
          muriatic acid gas
          
        </term>
            </rs> discovered by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag83"
                ref="#person_016"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag83" type="person">
          Priestly
        </name>
            </rs>.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">before</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">when</add>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <unclear>
                  <rs xml:id="ttag84" ref="#person_049" type="person">
                     <name xml:id="tag84" type="person">
          Guyton de Morveau
        </name>
                  </rs>
               </unclear>
            </hi> used it for<lb/>
destroying contagion. Consider the varied<lb/>
&amp; diversified application of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag85"
                ref="#chemical_369"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag85">
          Platinum
          
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
which has owed its existence as a useful<lb/>
metal entirely to the labours <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">an illustrious</add> chemical<lb/>
philosopher. Look at the beautiful yellow<lb/>
afforded by one of the new metals -<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag86" ref="#chemical_381" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag86">
          Chrome
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
Consider the medical effect of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
