from facts; &amp; all the arguments supporting<lb/>
it are derived from the modern discoveries<lb/>
in Chemistry. I shall often have occasion<lb/>
to refer to this part of the subject, &amp; I<lb/>
will proceed in offering you examples<lb/>
of the second important circumstances, namely<lb/>
that <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">bodies</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">bodies</add> combine with different degrees<lb/>
of force; &amp; in consequence that the <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">separation</add> separation<lb/>
of certain elements may be effected by<lb/>
the attraction of other elements. If<lb/>
            <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">xx</unclear>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag125"
                ref="#chemical_011"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag125">
          Magnesia
          
        </term>
            </rs> be dissolved in an acid<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="88"
                xml:id="pb-88"
