life, or by the efforts of man, by<lb/>
gravitation constantly tends to the<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <unclear> common</unclear>
            </add>
            <lb/>
Centre of attraction; &amp; the great<lb/>
reason of the duration of the Pyramid<lb/>
above other forms is, that it is the<lb/>
most fitted to resist the force of<lb/>
gravitation. The arch, the pillar, &amp;<lb/>
all perpendicular constructions are liable<lb/>
to fall when a degradation from<lb/>
Chemical or mechanical causes takes<lb/>
place in their inferior parts. The forms<lb/>
upon the surface of the globe are<lb/>
preserved from the influence of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="209"
