            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">I first described</add> are sufficient to account for the<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">effects</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">results</add> of time. But the physical<lb/>
powers of nature in producing decay<lb/>
are assisted likewise by certain<lb/>
agencies or energies of organized beings<lb/>
A polished surface of a building or<lb/>
a statue, is no sooner made rough<lb/>
from the causes that have been referred<lb/>
to, than the seeds of lichens &amp; mosses<lb/>
which are constantly floating in<lb/>
our atmosphere make it a place of <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">repose, grow &amp; increase</add>
